english:
  title: A Memorial Against Buddhism
  author: Eo Byeon-gap
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servants humbly submit that the harms wrought by the Buddha dharma are of long standing. Since the Han dynasty, reverence for it has only grown more fervent, yet the historical records show no blessing received—a truth Your Highness well knows. Why then need we speak further?

    Consider the arguments of Han Yu: "In ancient times, people engaged in four occupations; today they pursue six. Where once one farmer fed one family, now six households depend on one farmer's grain. Where once one craftsman served one family, now six households use one craftsman's tools. Where once one merchant sustained one family, now six households draw upon his trade. Is it any wonder then that the people grow poor and turn to banditry?" And he continues: "The people produce grain and silk, fashion vessels, and circulate goods to serve their superiors. Should they refuse, punishment follows." Though Han Yu's understanding of governance may be incomplete, his words deserve consideration, and we humbly beseech Your Highness to take them to heart.

    Your servants further hold that among heterodox teachings, none is more pernicious than Buddhism. It bears the customs of barbarian lands, stands outside the four estates of society, yet causes the people to impoverish and steal. What punishment could be too severe for such transgression?

    When wild beasts consume grain, we drive them far away—because they harm the people. Yet beasts, though they eat what humans have produced, at least provide us benefit. But monks who sit idle and consume—what benefit do they bring? In this time of drought and flood, when harvests fail and our granaries empty, the people face uncertainty in life and death itself. Yet these mendicants eat equally in abundance or scarcity. We see hungry people; we do not see hungry monks. We see people starving to death; we never see monks starving to death. Day by day they seduce and deceive, secretly draining the very lifeblood of the people. How can we not grieve?

    Ancient sages spoke long of these harms. Statesmen censured Buddhism for devouring wealth and confounding the people. Moralists rejected it for denying father and sovereign. Scholars condemned it for promoting emptiness and extinction, undermining true learning. Yet its doctrines are grand and sweeping, readily captivating human hearts. Like murky waters permeating all things, it has saturated ten thousand years. Rulers have nearly fallen into its snare; ministers and officials have nearly been trapped; the ignorant masses, orphans and widows, have nearly been deceived—and few have awakened. This is because true learning remains obscure and human hearts uncorrected. Rulers have not perfected the way of utmost sincerity and constancy; ministers have not exhausted the learning of investigating things and rectifying the mind. Fearing retribution and craving reward, they easily succumb to talk of karma and causal consequence. The unlearned people follow their desires and mimic those above, thus falling ever more readily into deception, and the world's customs have been swept away.

    If there arose a ruler like Yao, Shun, or the Kings Wen and Wu, or a minister like Gao Yao, Qi, Duke Zhou, or Duke Shao, they would not merely condemn those men and burn their books—they would execute them with exemplary punishment to warn against heterodoxy. How much less would they permit such men to dwell in great mansions and feast on delicacies, receiving the offerings of incense worship? How could they allow them to shave their heads, dye their robes black, escape taxation, and accumulate property? How could they permit them to achieve official rank and status, wearing purple robes alongside the highest ministers, parading through the capital?

    This is why pure precepts go unheeded while shameful practices multiply daily. Our Great King Taejong, inheriting the legacy of his illustrious predecessor and the accumulated habits of the former dynasty, renewed sacred learning, strengthened the bonds of society, reformed the system of recommendation, and built no temple halls for state rituals. With learned ministers like Ha Ryun assisting him, he made it his constant concern to suppress heterodoxy and pacify the people. He reformed monasteries and reduced their lands—sowing the seeds of minor correction to demonstrate the intent of major reform.

    Now Your Highness, endowed with robust and refined qualities and blessed with innate understanding of right learning, bearing the weighty charge entrusted by your august father, stands at a moment to accomplish great deeds. To follow the noble intentions of your predecessors, illuminate teaching, rectify the human heart, uphold true learning, and banish heterodoxy—so that the Way shines brilliant as the sun at noon—this is a moment when half the effort yields double the fruit.

    Some argue that since family temples are now established and the rites of water and land are settled, their force has already weakened, and people will naturally know the way and gradually turn to the family rites. Yet even among the educated, when death and mourning come suddenly, those directing the rites grow confused and cannot properly manage each matter—how much less can the unlearned do so? Moreover, human nature loves custom and dreads reform. Though superiors model proper conduct, people will not follow uniformly.

    Though the water-and-land rites are simplified, the nation cannot suddenly abolish them entirely. Old customs of memorial offerings and birthday blessings persist among the great ministers themselves. If the superior class cannot escape these, how can the common people? When the above permits this and forbids that, the people lose faith. Thus all people, regardless of status or wealth, say, "The family rites are good"—yet should they practice them, others call them strange. "The water-and-land rites are simple"—yet should they practice them, others call them stingy.

    They rush to monasteries, feed the Buddha and the monks, summon friends for competition in extravagance, wasteful expenditure beyond measure. The rich exhaust their fortunes; the poor take loans from both state and private lenders. After the forty-nine day memorial rites, they have no strength for burial. When burial is complete, creditors press them day and night. Thus they mortgage and sell their fields and houses to repay debts, and the people cannot survive. This, Your Highness may not yet know, but it grieves your servants deeply.

    Consider that prosperity must yield to decline—such is the way of things. Virtue receives reward, transgression brings calamity—such is Heaven's principle. Yao, Shun, Yu, Tang, Kings Wen and Wu, Duke Zhou—these are the great sages of all under Heaven. Their achievements have benefited both their age and all ages; all people revere them—yet they receive no such temples. What god is this Buddha, speaking words of delusion that corrupt the celestial order, stealing the sovereign's authority to command all the world's people? Truly, the Buddha is the enemy of Yu, Tang, Wen, Wu, and Zhou—yet enjoys what even these could not. His transgression is absolute.

    A man must strike himself before others strike him. The cases of the monks Dojing and Seolryeon, and the incidents at Hoiamsa and Jingwansa, serve as mirrors for us. Yet look at the endless succession of evils among the monks of Heungcheongsa. Is this not the exhaustion of fortune and accumulation of wickedness, with Heaven itself detesting it, causing these roots to wither, awaiting only Your Highness's divine judgment?

    Mengzi rejected the words of deceivers, concealers, and escapists while claiming to inherit the tradition of the three sages. Later generations judged his achievement to be no less than Yu's. We humbly beseech Your Highness: sweep away the barbarous dharma, transform the customs of the land. Dismantle the stupas and temples, burn the sutras and vinaya texts. Cause all monks and nuns to return to lay life. Command the Ministry of Rites to model their mourning and sacrificial rites upon Master Zhu's Family Rites, making them fit for both ministers and common people. Let ritual ranks have proper gradations, garments and vessels have fixed measures. Present these through diagrams clear and simple, so even the dullest peasant can understand and practice them. Then those who once idled and consumed will become tillers of the soil. Those who once sought Buddha's blessings will become sons of filial piety and ancestral reverence. The Way will be unified, the realm will know one custom, the human heart will be upright, true learning will flourish, and the world's conduct will become pure and sincere—achieving the golden age of the Eastern Zhou.

    Thus shall Your Highness's great learning and labors shine brilliantly in the records, so that later generations know the deeds of our great sage surpass ordinary measure ten thousand times over. This will purify human hearts, rectify the world's ways, and establish blessings for ten thousand ages without end. Herein lies all true accomplishment.

    Your servants, though of humble capacity, stand near the brilliant light of Your Highness. Our duty is to think, discuss, and advance virtue to aid your noble character. Yet we have offered no words before. Fortunately, we now hear that the Censorate has addressed this matter. Seizing this opportunity, we cannot contain our joy. We have heard that Yi Yin believed: should he fail to make his sovereign equal to Yao and Shun, he would feel as one beaten in the marketplace. Thus we venture to raise this matter, respectfully beseeching your sage judgment and action. Should Your Highness implement these measures, it shall be the greatest fortune for the realm and for the Way itself.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Han Yu (768-824), Tang dynasty scholar-official and Confucian thinker, whose "Memorial on the Bone of the Buddha" is a classic text against Buddhism in East Asia.
  - key: ''
    value: 'The four estates (sadaehyung: 士農工商) were the traditional social hierarchy in Confucian society: scholars, farmers, artisans, and merchants. The memorial argues that monasticism and Daoism add unproductive classes.'
  - key: ''
    value: Water-and-land rites (suryuk) were elaborate Buddhist ceremonies believed to save souls; the memorial criticizes their expense and the people's attachment to them despite official efforts at reform.
  - key: ''
    value: The forty-nine day memorial rites (49-jae) were Buddhist observances following death; the memorial laments the financial ruin these cause through required temple feasts and donations.
  - key: ''
    value: Yi Yin was a legendary minister of the Shang dynasty, celebrated in Confucian tradition as the ideal counselor who would face any hardship rather than allow his sovereign to fall short of sagely virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: Master Zhu refers to Zhu Xi (1130-1200), the Neo-Confucian philosopher whose Family Rites (Jiali) became the standard for ritual practice and whom Korean Confucians deeply revered.
